ger speak their language and the Beijing dialect of Chinese replaced it because of the influence from the nation that they were in despite the incentives from the Qing government. After the Qing dynasty ended, most Manchu speakers were scared to speak it because the Han people were in charge of China again. Nowadays, Mandarin Chinese is needed to work and live in modern-day China.%0a%3c %0a%3c There are revitalization efforts in place that are linked to the reconstruction of the ethnic Manchu identity in China. This began in the post-Mao era and now has support from many NGOs and other minority ethnic groups in China. These organizations offer classes at primary schools and universities, using it as a mechanism to teach reading of Qing dynasty texts. However, there are still many difficulties because China is a Han-dominated country and is still thought of as a foreign language.%0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c https://www.lakeforest.edu/academics/majors-and-minors/environmental-studies/the-manchu-language%0a%3c https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manchu_language%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
